result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (2nd) and Operating w/ PAC (2nd). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (2nd) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (2nd) was dismissed by the court.

  • Sabra Alison Tyrer was found guilty of OWI (2nd), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Sabra Alison Tyrer in court with attorney Patricia M. Padurean.   District Attorney's Office Law Intern, Katrina Seipel, appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Arguments by the Defense.  Statement by defendant.  

Court orders the following: 
- 5 months Huber with standard release conditions. STAYED
- 1 year Probation
- 18 months Drivers License Revocation. 
- 18 months Ignition Interlock on any vehicle TITLED OR REGISTERED to defendant 
- Alcohol Assessment
- Attendance at the Victim Impact Panel meeting on either August 19, 2015 or the following one, or 30 days jail consecutive.
- Fine of 1,179.00; cash bail to be applied.  Any remaining fine to be paid as a Condition of Probation
- Blood Test Reimbursement of $35.00 paid through Waukesha County Circuit Court to be forwarded to Delafield Police Department

Valid prescriptions to be taken in the manner they were prescribed.  Continue with Mental Health treatment/counseling.  Attend a minimum of 2 self help meetings per week.
